May 11 2009 	Great Location But Dated	Have stayed at the Prescott on several occasions while on business in SF. Usually get great rates for 4-star on Priceline and Prescott is a top choice.First off, the hotel is tucked away with a very unassuming front right off of Union Square. You have to look for it hard or you might miss it. It is a boutique hotel and once in the lobby, you get the sense immediately. The lobby is tight but quaint and never had a problem at check-in. Staff is great and very friendly. The rooms are a bit dated now. Most are in need of refurbish and do not meet the standards of a true 4-star as listed. On the plus side, most of the rooms are very large for a city hotel. Even though a bit tarnished, the rooms are always spotless and in good order. Lots of unusual hallways similar to other old hotels. They have a great wine tasting in the lobby daily and the Club Level is very nice. I'm not usally into that stuff but found myself a couple of times having a glass and meeting some other travelers. Most are from Europe and Latin America. Very interesting.In-room amenities are great. Sucker for a mini-bar and has a great one. Wireless and wired internet with good functional desk and chair. Lots of windows though usually your view is of other rooms, but natural light.They have an attached restuarant. Only had breakfast that was very good and reasonably priced for hotel ($17). Parking is terrible - but its that way anywhere in SF. $45-night and you must valet.The location is great. Just off Union Square and walkable to just about anywhere. We walked over to North Beach to eat Italian. It was especially great after dinner walking off that great meal at North Beach Italian (must try). You go right through China town. If you pick the right streets, you miss any big hills.Summary - if you get it cheap, a great hotel find. Not a true 4-star anymore, but would recommend for all the little things.	
